<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="359" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1628,2015]" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1628,1655]" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof" authorityYear="2020" box="[281,570,1629,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Monardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abbreviata" subGenus="Xylopriona">
<emphasis box="[281,392,1629,1655]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">Monardia</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[409,434,1630,1655]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">X.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[450,570,1629,1655]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">abbreviata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Berest &amp; Mamaev" authorityName="Berest &amp; Mamaev" authorityYear="1997" box="[697,1109,1629,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Monardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unguifera" subGenus="Xylopriona">
<emphasis box="[697,728,1630,1655]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">M.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[745,769,1630,1655]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">X.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[786,895,1629,1655]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">unguifera</emphasis>
Berest &amp; Mamaev
</taxonomicName>
in possessing a 4-segmented palpus (other species described of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Felt" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[602,744,1665,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Monardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="toxicodendri">
<emphasis box="[602,744,1665,1691]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">toxicodendri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group have 3-segmented palpi, but see the remark below). Differences between these two species are as follows. The aedeagal apodeme of 
<emphasis box="[1074,1105,1702,1727]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">M.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof" authorityYear="2020" box="[1114,1285,1701,1727]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Monardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abbreviata" subGenus="Xylopriona">
(
<emphasis box="[1123,1140,1702,1727]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">X</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1165,1285,1701,1727]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">abbreviata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
consists of a strongly sclerotized, rodlike portion basally and a broader, vaguely contoured portion apically, both equally long (
<figureCitation box="[160,242,1773,1799]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1807,1832]" captionTargetBox="[179,1406,464,1770]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[170,1416,453,1782]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Male morphology of Monardia (Xylopriona) abbreviata (15–16) and Monardia (Xyl.) obscura (17–18), holotypes. 15: Fourth flagellomere, lateral. 16: Genitalia, ventral. 17: Genitalia, ventral. 18: Fourth flagellomere, lateral. Scales 0.05 mm. Arrows refer to characters described in the diagnoses." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3707466" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3707466/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
, ↓ 
<superScript attach="none" box="[268,276,1772,1786]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">1</superScript>
); in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berest &amp; Mamaev" authorityYear="1997" box="[329,525,1773,1799]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Monardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unguifera" subGenus="Xylopriona">
<emphasis box="[329,360,1774,1799]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">M.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[375,400,1774,1799]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">X.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[416,525,1773,1799]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">unguifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the rod is markedly longer than the broadened, sharply contoured apex (
<bibRefCitation author="Jaschhof, M. &amp; Jaschhof, C." pageId="9" pageNumber="358" pagination="1 - 333" refId="ref13620" refString="Jaschhof, M. &amp; Jaschhof, C. (2009) The Wood Midges (Diptera: Cecidomyiidae: Lestremiinae) of Fennoscandia and Denmark. Studia dipterologica Supplement, 18, 1 - 333." type="journal article" year="2009">Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof 2009</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 71B). In both species the tegmen has a broadly rounded apical portion, which in 
<emphasis box="[1311,1342,1810,1835]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">M.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Monardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abbreviata" subGenus="Xylopriona">
(
<emphasis box="[1358,1375,1810,1835]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">X</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">abbreviata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considerably longer (↓ 
<superScript attach="none" box="[531,539,1844,1858]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">2</superScript>
) compared with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berest &amp; Mamaev" authorityYear="1997" box="[732,930,1845,1871]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Monardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unguifera" subGenus="Xylopriona">
<emphasis box="[732,763,1846,1871]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">M.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[780,805,1846,1871]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">X.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[821,930,1845,1871]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">unguifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Finally, the ventral gonocoxal emargination is V-shaped in 
<emphasis box="[316,347,1882,1907]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">M.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof" authorityYear="2020" box="[353,523,1881,1907]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Monardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abbreviata" subGenus="Xylopriona">
(
<emphasis box="[362,379,1882,1907]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">X</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[403,523,1881,1907]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">abbreviata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(↓ 
<superScript attach="none" box="[553,561,1880,1894]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">3</superScript>
) as opposed to U-shaped in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berest &amp; Mamaev" authorityYear="1997" box="[878,1074,1881,1907]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Monardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unguifera" subGenus="Xylopriona">
<emphasis box="[878,909,1882,1907]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">M.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[925,949,1882,1907]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">X.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[965,1074,1881,1907]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">unguifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Jaschhof, M. &amp; Jaschhof, C." box="[1088,1388,1881,1907]" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" pagination="1 - 333" refId="ref13620" refString="Jaschhof, M. &amp; Jaschhof, C. (2009) The Wood Midges (Diptera: Cecidomyiidae: Lestremiinae) of Fennoscandia and Denmark. Studia dipterologica Supplement, 18, 1 - 333." type="journal article" year="2009">Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof 2009</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 71A). Females and larvae of 
<emphasis box="[476,499,1918,1943]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">M</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof" authorityYear="2020" box="[513,683,1917,1943]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Monardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abbreviata" subGenus="Xylopriona">
(
<emphasis box="[523,540,1918,1943]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">X</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[563,683,1917,1943]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">abbreviata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1628,2015]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1437,152,431]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="359" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,476,1952,1979]" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">Other male characters.</emphasis>
Body size 
<quantity box="[602,741,1953,1979]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="9" pageNumber="358" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="1.1">1.1–1.2 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[752,823,1953,1979]" pageId="9" pageNumber="358">Head.</emphasis>
Postfrons setose. Eye bridge 2–3 ommatidia long dorsally. 9 postocular bristles. Fourth flagellomere with neck and node equally long; node with 1 complete and 2 incomplete crenulate whorls of sensory hairs, 2 roundish, leaf-shaped translucent sensilla distally (
<figureCitation box="[1257,1341,152,179]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1807,1832]" captionTargetBox="[179,1406,464,1770]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[170,1416,453,1782]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Male morphology of Monardia (Xylopriona) abbreviata (15–16) and Monardia (Xyl.) obscura (17–18), holotypes. 15: Fourth flagellomere, lateral. 16: Genitalia, ventral. 17: Genitalia, ventral. 18: Fourth flagellomere, lateral. Scales 0.05 mm. Arrows refer to characters described in the diagnoses." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3707466" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3707466/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="359">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Palpus shorter than head height. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[438,534,189,215]" pageId="10" pageNumber="359">Thorax.</emphasis>
Pronotum setose. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[743,815,188,215]" pageId="10" pageNumber="359">Wing.</emphasis>
R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[841,849,206,220]" fontSize="6" pageId="10" pageNumber="359">1</subScript>
2.5–3.0 times as long as Rs. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1181,1244,189,215]" pageId="10" pageNumber="359">Legs.</emphasis>
Claws toothless. Empodia nearly as long as claws. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[544,654,224,251]" pageId="10" pageNumber="359">Genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[671,757,225,252]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1807,1832]" captionTargetBox="[179,1406,464,1770]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[170,1416,453,1782]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Male morphology of Monardia (Xylopriona) abbreviata (15–16) and Monardia (Xyl.) obscura (17–18), holotypes. 15: Fourth flagellomere, lateral. 16: Genitalia, ventral. 17: Genitalia, ventral. 18: Fourth flagellomere, lateral. Scales 0.05 mm. Arrows refer to characters described in the diagnoses." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3707466" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3707466/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="359">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
). Ninth tergite almost interrupted medially, inside with two short, pigmented (sclerotized?) lappets (which in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berest &amp; Mamaev" authorityYear="1997" box="[703,899,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Monardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="359" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unguifera" subGenus="Xylopriona">
<emphasis box="[703,734,262,287]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="359">M.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[750,775,262,287]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="359">X.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[790,899,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="359">unguifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are much larger, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Jaschhof, M. &amp; Jaschhof, C." box="[1135,1432,261,287]" pageId="10" pageNumber="359" pagination="1 - 333" refId="ref13620" refString="Jaschhof, M. &amp; Jaschhof, C. (2009) The Wood Midges (Diptera: Cecidomyiidae: Lestremiinae) of Fennoscandia and Denmark. Studia dipterologica Supplement, 18, 1 - 333." type="journal article" year="2009">Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof 2009</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 71C). Gonocoxal synsclerite broader than long; a non-setose, membranous triangle medially below the emargination does not reach to the ventroanterior gonocoxal edge; dorsal bridge with slightly sinuous anterior edge. Gonostylus in ventral view about as long as broad; apical tooth gently bent, slightly shorter than gonostylar body. Tegmen with rounded rather than sharply angular shoulders.
</paragraph>
